  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 10, 11.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "A father",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is not a common application of the word father in the Old Testament. The prominent idea seems to be one of honour, combined with authority to teach and advise. It is applied to prophets (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 2:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 6:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 13:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and to Joseph (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 45:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The idea is implied in the converse phrase of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "son",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", applied to those to whom the prophets stood in 'the relation of spiritual fathers (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 4:10, 20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and frequently elsewhere). The abuse of the feeling which dictates the term as applied to human teachers is reproved by our Lord (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 23:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It has been freely used in the Christian Church, as in the titles ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "papa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "pope",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " applied to bishops, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "abbot",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "abbas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "father in God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fathers of the Church",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Here there is perhaps a special reference to the function of Micah's priest to ask counsel of God, and then give that counsel to those who came to inquire (see note to ver. 5). It may be added that the idea of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "counsellor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " seems to be inherent in the word cohen or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "priest",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Ten shekels",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - a little over a pound of our money, but probably equivalent to £20, when considered relatively to articles of consumption. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "A suit of apparel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". There is great doubt as to the exact meaning of the word rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "suit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in this connection. The word means anything ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "arranged",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " put in a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "rank",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "row",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "order.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 40:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is applied to the shewbread: \"He ordered the bread in order.\" Thence it came to mean the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "estimation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "worth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of a person or thing - some-what as we use the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "rank.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " From this last sense some interpret the word here to mean the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "worth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "price",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of his clothes. Others, including St. Jerome and the Septuagint, interpret it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a pair",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of vestments, meaning summer and winter clothing. But perhaps the A.V., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "suit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", meaning the whole set of under and upper garments, is after all the best interpretation. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The Levite went in",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Hebrew is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "went",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " according to the common use of the word, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "went his way.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " And such is probably the meaning here. He went his way to consider the proposal made to him. The result is given in the next verse: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "And the Levite was content",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Judges 17:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
